  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Respiratory muscle dysfunction in critically ill patients is associated with elevated
      morbidity, including prolonged weaning from mechanical ventilation. The causes for
      respiratory muscle dysfunction in these patients is poorly understood and no effective
      treatment is available.

      The general hypothesis of the present study is that in critically ill mechanically ventilated
      subjects respiratory muscle dysfunctions results from loss of myosin induced by activation of
      proteolytic cascades.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
